1
00:00:01,000 --> 00:00:04,074
Subtitles downloaded from Podnapisi.NET

2
00:01:51,367 --> 00:01:53,559
What a way to enter Italy.

3
00:01:55,300 --> 00:01:58,061
Absolutely. The ideal way.

4
00:02:00,367 --> 00:02:03,662
Land of fertility, fine women...

5
00:02:05,066 --> 00:02:06,895
inimitable history...

6
00:02:08,699 --> 00:02:11,756
home of the dome and the arch,
good food...

7
00:02:12,933 --> 00:02:14,523
and high ideals.

8
00:02:15,633 --> 00:02:19,565
High ideals? My father was Italian...

9
00:02:19,966 --> 00:02:22,091
and he was very thin.

10
00:02:22,300 --> 00:02:24,822
He was only interested in money.

11
00:02:24,900 --> 00:02:26,798
Yes, and carnivorous enough.

12
00:02:27,866 --> 00:02:31,128
He had no ideals except
to leave this place.

13
00:02:31,799 --> 00:02:35,232
Well, he was idealistic enough
to take all that money to Chicago.

14
00:02:35,532 --> 00:02:39,363
City of blood, meat, and money.

15
00:02:40,866 --> 00:02:44,923
Home of some of the best carnivorous
architecture in the Western world.

16
00:02:45,799 --> 00:02:47,662
That is, of course, outside of Rome.

17
00:04:14,400 --> 00:04:17,957
It's really beautiful. This is really good.

18
00:04:18,599 --> 00:04:21,724
Friends, <i>amici, Signor</i> Kracklite.

19
00:04:22,300 --> 00:04:25,198
May I speak formally
on behalf of all of us...

20
00:04:25,267 --> 00:04:27,994
to say how pleased we are...

21
00:04:28,066 --> 00:04:32,226
to welcome such a celebrated
American architect to Rome.

22
00:04:33,733 --> 00:04:37,722
And we wish you and your wife...

23
00:04:38,233 --> 00:04:40,994
all the best wishes on your birthday.

24
00:04:42,400 --> 00:04:47,059
We know that the exhibition
of Étienne-Louis Boullée...

25
00:04:47,566 --> 00:04:51,521
you do us the honor of
presenting here in Rome...

26
00:04:51,599 --> 00:04:54,861
will be a resounding success.

27
00:04:59,666 --> 00:05:01,495
<i>Signor</i> Speckler, thank you.

28
00:05:01,633 --> 00:05:02,894
My friends...

29
00:05:03,400 --> 00:05:06,230
we both would like to
thank you very sincerely...

30
00:05:06,300 --> 00:05:08,095
for your very warm welcome.

31
00:05:08,633 --> 00:05:11,065
Boullée's crowning achievement...

32
00:05:11,432 --> 00:05:14,297
inspired, of course,
by the magnificent building...

33
00:05:14,566 --> 00:05:16,725
of the Pantheon, here, behind us...

34
00:05:18,833 --> 00:05:22,458
was a memorial he designed
in honor of Sir Isaac Newton...

35
00:05:22,532 --> 00:05:24,794
for whom Boullée had great reverence.

36
00:05:25,599 --> 00:05:29,497
Now, I doubt whether Sir Isaac Newton
has ever before been celebrated...

37
00:05:29,566 --> 00:05:32,032
with sugar icing.

38
00:05:34,267 --> 00:05:36,028
However, for me...

39
00:05:36,799 --> 00:05:39,231
having waited so many years...

40
00:05:39,300 --> 00:05:42,697
to honor this visionary architect...

41
00:05:43,799 --> 00:05:47,561
whom I have so passionately admired
ever since I was a child...

42
00:05:49,100 --> 00:05:50,396
For me...

43
00:05:51,267 --> 00:05:54,392
this moment is very sweet indeed.

44
00:05:59,133 --> 00:06:02,530
Étienne-Louis Boullée!

45
00:06:07,532 --> 00:06:10,430
Now, with your permission,
I'd like to call upon my wife...

46
00:06:10,499 --> 00:06:12,795
to cut this magnificent cake.

47
00:06:12,866 --> 00:06:17,299
I can assure you that she is very
experienced in opening supermarkets...

48
00:06:18,033 --> 00:06:20,692
kissing babies, christening ships...

49
00:06:20,866 --> 00:06:23,025
and cutting the tape.

50
00:06:36,367 --> 00:06:39,457
Sir Isaac Newton,
the subject of tonight's cake...

51
00:06:39,699 --> 00:06:41,961
appears in every Englishman's wallet.

52
00:06:42,200 --> 00:06:46,030
A man who discovers gravity
must be a very good companion.

53
00:06:46,432 --> 00:06:49,228
In fixing us firmly on the earth...

54
00:06:49,367 --> 00:06:53,492
he enables us with equanimity
to keep our head in the clouds.

55
00:06:55,866 --> 00:06:59,525
If you look carefully,
you can spot a reference to gravity.

56
00:06:59,699 --> 00:07:01,325
See if you can find it.

57
00:07:01,499 --> 00:07:04,227
It's an English note.
So, of course, it's laconic.

58
00:07:04,833 --> 00:07:06,958
It's there, the apple blossom.

59
00:07:07,599 --> 00:07:09,190
I hear, <i>Signor</i> Kracklite...

60
00:07:09,267 --> 00:07:12,199
that your inspiration
for the Chicago-Angelo Building...

61
00:07:12,267 --> 00:07:15,233
came entirely from the
profit on sausages.

62
00:07:16,033 --> 00:07:18,794
No. Frankfurters, hot dogs...

63
00:07:18,866 --> 00:07:22,525
hamburgers, salami, baloney.

64
00:07:23,466 --> 00:07:25,659
A monument to carnivores.

65
00:07:27,100 --> 00:07:30,725
In Chicago,
they call it the slaughterhouse.

66
00:07:31,532 --> 00:07:35,329
A building suffering from
excess cholesterol...

67
00:07:36,000 --> 00:07:37,488
like Stourley.

68
00:07:37,566 --> 00:07:40,555
No. There's no excess fat on it, or me.

69
00:07:41,000 --> 00:07:42,625
The both of us have been built...

70
00:07:42,699 --> 00:07:46,359
with perfect and enviable
centers of gravity.

71
00:07:46,466 --> 00:07:50,592
- Standing up?
- No, <i>Signora</i> Speckler, lying down.

72
00:07:56,566 --> 00:07:59,362
How long have you been married to him?

73
00:08:00,000 --> 00:08:01,364
Seven years.

74
00:08:02,933 --> 00:08:05,421
Why? Do you think that's too long?

75
00:08:16,933 --> 00:08:19,399
God! I think I've lost my English £1 note.

76
00:08:19,466 --> 00:08:21,659
Come on, you can easily get another.

77
00:08:22,233 --> 00:08:24,858
No, you can't.
They're dropping out of circulation.

78
00:08:25,133 --> 00:08:27,099
My father's wedding present...

79
00:08:27,699 --> 00:08:30,529
was another commission for Kracklite...

80
00:08:31,033 --> 00:08:32,521
to build us a house.

81
00:08:33,900 --> 00:08:35,593
You should see it.

82
00:08:35,666 --> 00:08:39,326
Two marble cubes and
a brick sphere on stilts.

83
00:08:40,799 --> 00:08:42,958
Boullée would have loved it.

84
00:08:43,933 --> 00:08:46,899
What do you think of
our foreign architect?

85
00:08:47,633 --> 00:08:49,656
He's too old for his wife.

86
00:08:50,367 --> 00:08:53,265
I think she's looking for
a romantic experience.

87
00:08:53,666 --> 00:08:55,030
How can you tell?

88
00:08:55,633 --> 00:08:57,259
The way she eats cake.

89
00:09:01,900 --> 00:09:04,593
Just about this time,
if I'm near the Pantheon...

90
00:09:04,666 --> 00:09:09,395
I come and admire such a
great work of architecture.

91
00:09:10,200 --> 00:09:13,325
As solid as it is beautiful.

92
00:09:14,267 --> 00:09:17,028
As romantic as it is awesome.

93
00:09:17,766 --> 00:09:21,721
Built by Hadrian, the most
accomplished of all the Emperors.

94
00:09:24,233 --> 00:09:27,199
Good architecture should
always be applauded.

95
00:10:32,333 --> 00:10:35,457
I notice Caspasian wears
a double-breasted suit.

96
00:10:36,333 --> 00:10:37,390
So?

97
00:10:38,466 --> 00:10:41,297
He wears a matching
tie bar and cuff links.

98
00:10:41,367 --> 00:10:44,457
I wouldn't be surprised
if he wore a gold chain around his neck.

99
00:10:44,532 --> 00:10:46,328
Do you want me to find out?

100
00:10:48,633 --> 00:10:50,724
Would you want to find out?

101
00:10:51,666 --> 00:10:53,394
It's not important.

102
00:10:57,200 --> 00:10:58,859
What is important?

103
00:11:00,900 --> 00:11:03,389
To be gracious to the Specklers.

104
00:11:03,766 --> 00:11:05,664
They have a lot of influence.

105
00:11:07,432 --> 00:11:09,898
- They have a lot of charm.
- Don't they?

106
00:11:10,200 --> 00:11:11,995
Especially Caspasian.

107
00:11:13,333 --> 00:11:16,423
Especially? Are you jealous?

108
00:11:18,300 --> 00:11:20,993
Of his charm? No.

109
00:11:22,833 --> 00:11:25,492
His gold chain? Absolutely not.

110
00:11:27,499 --> 00:11:29,022
Of his youth...

111
00:11:33,666 --> 00:11:37,621
Of his youth and his waistline, maybe.

112
00:11:39,200 --> 00:11:41,529
Of his ability as an architect?

113
00:11:43,367 --> 00:11:45,356
No, that least of all.

114
00:11:45,432 --> 00:11:48,592
I'm sure Mr. Caspasian
is devoid of talent.

115
00:12:11,666 --> 00:12:14,496
Tell me, please,
what does "oh-ah" mean?

116
00:12:16,666 --> 00:12:20,394
Stourley, you've built
six-and-a-half buildings.

117
00:12:20,566 --> 00:12:22,532
And now you're spending nine months...

118
00:12:22,599 --> 00:12:25,690
putting on an exhibition
in memory of another architect...

119
00:12:25,766 --> 00:12:28,425
who also built practically nothing.

120
00:12:28,933 --> 00:12:30,229
And I don't...

121
00:12:32,267 --> 00:12:34,562
What? What's the matter?

122
00:12:35,400 --> 00:12:36,888
- I don't know.
- What?

123
00:12:41,066 --> 00:12:42,225
Indigestion.

124
00:12:45,000 --> 00:12:46,364
You eat too much.

125
00:12:50,733 --> 00:12:53,131
Nothing a little sympathy wouldn't cure.

126
00:12:59,799 --> 00:13:03,129
What's this? Twice in one day?

127
00:13:11,066 --> 00:13:12,725
What about Boullée?

128
00:13:14,400 --> 00:13:16,865
Now, he built virtually nothing...

129
00:13:17,566 --> 00:13:19,055
and look at his reputation.

130
00:13:19,133 --> 00:13:21,361
Yeah. Look at it.

131
00:13:21,532 --> 00:13:23,794
Nobody knows about him but you.

132
00:13:24,699 --> 00:13:29,155
You think that they'll give you an
exhibition 180 years after your death?

133
00:13:29,966 --> 00:13:32,159
Death? Who's talking about death?

134
00:13:32,699 --> 00:13:35,961
Doesn't everyone in
Rome talk about death?

135
00:13:42,699 --> 00:13:45,029
- What's the matter?
- Wait.

136
00:13:45,599 --> 00:13:46,963
- What?
- No!

137
00:13:50,633 --> 00:13:52,099
No, it's all right.

138
00:13:53,233 --> 00:13:54,630
My stomach.

139
00:13:57,300 --> 00:14:01,732
It serves you right.
You're always stuffing yourself.

140
00:14:08,432 --> 00:14:10,557
Don't start what you can't finish.

141
00:15:09,033 --> 00:15:12,158
<i>Romans are very equivocal
about this building.</i>

142
00:15:13,066 --> 00:15:16,896
<i>They call it the Typewriter
or the Wedding Cake.</i>

143
00:15:17,333 --> 00:15:21,026
<i>It's like a box at the theater</i>
<i>at which Rome is the play.</i>

144
00:15:22,200 --> 00:15:24,461
Over there, you can see the Colosseum.

145
00:15:26,532 --> 00:15:30,124
There, Michelangelo's
dome of San Pietro.

146
00:15:31,966 --> 00:15:34,091
And over there, you can just see...

147
00:15:34,166 --> 00:15:37,326
Borromini's Church of
Sant'Agnese in Piazza Navona.

148
00:15:39,166 --> 00:15:41,291
Where is the Tomb of
Augustus from here?

149
00:15:41,367 --> 00:15:44,026
Difficult to see from here,
<i>Signor</i> Kracklite.

150
00:15:44,100 --> 00:15:45,690
But undoubtedly there.

151
00:15:47,066 --> 00:15:49,362
<i>Signor</i> Kracklite,
let me introduce to you...

152
00:15:49,432 --> 00:15:52,228
<i>Signor</i> Antonio Caspetti,
banker with the Scuta d'Oro.

153
00:15:52,300 --> 00:15:55,061
<i>Signor</i> Caspetti
is our most important benefactor.

154
00:15:55,133 --> 00:15:57,826
We couldn't manage this
exhibition without him.

155
00:15:58,633 --> 00:16:00,496
And after its undoubted success...

156
00:16:00,566 --> 00:16:03,623
can I hope to consider
a return exhibition in Chicago?

157
00:16:04,333 --> 00:16:07,299
Perhaps on the Italian architect Piranesi.

158
00:16:07,466 --> 00:16:10,399
<i>Signor</i> Caspetti is a great
authority on Piranesi.

159
00:16:11,100 --> 00:16:15,691
I wonder if Kracklite realizes that his
hero is not that well-known in Italy.

160
00:16:16,000 --> 00:16:18,364
Boullée is not that well-known anywhere.

161
00:16:19,367 --> 00:16:23,231
In Texas,
Kracklite was accused of inventing him.

162
00:16:23,699 --> 00:16:27,995
Or perhaps Boullée is the ideal architect
for your husband to invent.

163
00:16:28,799 --> 00:16:30,356
However, thanks to him...

164
00:16:30,432 --> 00:16:33,990
we have nearly $1 million to
persuade the Italian public...

165
00:16:34,066 --> 00:16:35,793
that Boullée is not a fiction.

166
00:16:35,866 --> 00:16:37,230
That's a lot of money.

167
00:16:37,300 --> 00:16:40,424
It's expensive to put on
a large art exhibition in Rome.

168
00:16:42,033 --> 00:16:45,556
I remember, <i>Signor</i> Kracklite,
coming across a drawing by Boullée...

169
00:16:45,633 --> 00:16:47,327
when I was 10 years old.

170
00:16:47,566 --> 00:16:50,089
It reminded me, I must admit, of Hell.

171
00:16:50,633 --> 00:16:52,895
No doubt it was a childish idea...

172
00:16:53,400 --> 00:16:55,389
but it hasn't entirely left me.

173
00:16:55,966 --> 00:16:59,489
I discovered Boullée about the
same age as you, <i>Signor</i> Caspetti.

174
00:16:59,599 --> 00:17:03,054
I must confess his designs
have always reminded me of Heaven.

175
00:17:04,066 --> 00:17:07,498
You hold the purse strings
of my husband's exhibition?

176
00:17:08,367 --> 00:17:10,696
Not entirely, but almost.

177
00:17:11,933 --> 00:17:15,161
You're very young to be
entrusted with so much money.

178
00:17:15,599 --> 00:17:19,259
And you're very young to be entrusted
with such an elderly husband.

179
00:17:22,066 --> 00:17:23,191
Excuse me.

180
00:17:25,400 --> 00:17:28,456
There is a story that the
architect of this building...

181
00:17:29,033 --> 00:17:32,090
spent all the money on the marble.
He didn't like wood.

182
00:17:32,566 --> 00:17:34,589
And he skimped on the carpentry.

183
00:17:34,799 --> 00:17:38,788
The real reason was that he hated
carpenters, especially Joseph.

184
00:17:39,333 --> 00:17:42,094
I suspect that he didn't
believe in the virgin birth.

185
00:17:42,166 --> 00:17:43,961
He could not reconcile himself...

186
00:17:44,033 --> 00:17:47,795
to the fact Joseph was 40
and the Virgin Mary was 14.

187
00:17:47,866 --> 00:17:50,832
About the same difference
as you and your wife...

188
00:17:51,400 --> 00:17:53,195
isn't it, Mr. Kracklite?

189
00:17:54,233 --> 00:17:55,664
Approximately, yes.

190
00:17:55,933 --> 00:17:58,797
But I thought that all Catholics
believed in the virgin birth.

191
00:17:58,866 --> 00:18:00,559
Not outside of marriage.

192
00:18:01,200 --> 00:18:04,132
Do you believe in the virgin birth,
Mr. Kracklite?

193
00:18:05,100 --> 00:18:08,362
At this moment, <i>Signor</i> Caspetti,
I'll settle for any kind of birth.

194
00:18:08,599 --> 00:18:10,690
I've had several miscarriages.

195
00:18:12,432 --> 00:18:15,489
Kracklite gets bored or impatient...

196
00:18:15,566 --> 00:18:18,032
or disillusioned with his projects...

197
00:18:18,200 --> 00:18:20,166
and I get anxious.

198
00:18:21,166 --> 00:18:24,598
We could both be accused
of unsatisfactory delivery.

199
00:18:25,267 --> 00:18:26,255
Christ!

200
00:18:26,866 --> 00:18:28,230
Did you see that?

201
00:18:29,766 --> 00:18:31,323
Now watch this.

202
00:18:32,233 --> 00:18:35,393
Kracklite is going to be
honored by Roman publicity.

203
00:18:36,400 --> 00:18:37,660
Who is this man?

204
00:18:37,733 --> 00:18:40,824
May I introduce to you
<i>Signor</i> Salvatore Battistino...

205
00:18:40,900 --> 00:18:43,627
the Secretary of the Society
of Historical Buildings.

206
00:18:43,699 --> 00:18:45,927
And an expert on nightclubs.

207
00:18:46,033 --> 00:18:48,022
May I? Dr. Trettorio.

208
00:18:48,333 --> 00:18:52,594
Dr. Trettorio is an expert
on the diseases of the ancient world.

209
00:19:08,233 --> 00:19:11,393
Are you a modern architect,
Mr. Kracklite?

210
00:19:11,666 --> 00:19:13,689
No more modern than I should be.

211
00:19:13,799 --> 00:19:16,265
No more modern than Boullée,
would you say?

212
00:19:16,400 --> 00:19:21,230
Replicas of whose buildings now
appear in every authoritarian
capital in the world.

213
00:19:21,532 --> 00:19:24,692
Moscow, Peking, East Berlin.

214
00:19:24,866 --> 00:19:26,764
And Rome, <i>Signorina</i> Speckler?

215
00:19:26,833 --> 00:19:29,492
Are you saying Boullée was
the first Fascist architect?

216
00:19:29,566 --> 00:19:30,657
Ask my brother.

217
00:19:30,733 --> 00:19:33,256
Do you think Mussolini admired Boullée?

218
00:19:33,333 --> 00:19:36,730
Albert Speer did,
and Speer was Hitler's architect.

219
00:19:37,033 --> 00:19:39,192
Augustus would have admired Boullée.

220
00:19:40,267 --> 00:19:42,392
Go to Via Ripetta. Look at his tomb.

221
00:19:42,466 --> 00:19:44,365
Don't encourage him, please.

222
00:19:45,333 --> 00:19:47,026
Augustus' wife chose it.

223
00:19:47,233 --> 00:19:50,028
But first she made sure
he would fit inside it...

224
00:19:50,233 --> 00:19:52,630
after all the trouble she had taken.

225
00:19:52,733 --> 00:19:54,995
- Trouble? What trouble?
- Poison.

226
00:19:56,666 --> 00:20:01,031
You see, Augustus felt this dryness
at the back of his throat...

227
00:20:01,100 --> 00:20:04,225
and then a cold shiver
across his shoulders.

228
00:20:04,900 --> 00:20:06,059
A pain...

229
00:20:07,166 --> 00:20:10,394
like a poker in the small of his back.
A desire to vomit.

230
00:20:10,566 --> 00:20:12,260
It was obviously poison.

231
00:20:12,733 --> 00:20:15,893
His neck became stiff,
his ears began to sing...

232
00:20:16,066 --> 00:20:17,531
his eyes to flutter.

233
00:20:17,599 --> 00:20:19,690
The buttons popped off his jacket...

234
00:20:19,766 --> 00:20:21,698
- Jacket? Are you sure?
- Yes.

235
00:20:21,766 --> 00:20:25,664
Caspasian believes everyone
of substance wears a suit.

236
00:20:25,833 --> 00:20:29,697
And a gallon of yellow bile
erupted from his mouth...

237
00:20:33,966 --> 00:20:37,057
Sorry, Flavia. It was just a history lesson.

238
00:20:39,267 --> 00:20:40,630
For foreigners.

239
00:21:35,200 --> 00:21:37,995
<i>Signor</i> Battistino. You all right?

240
00:21:38,966 --> 00:21:40,693
Of course he's all right.

241
00:21:48,000 --> 00:21:50,488
It sounded like he was dying
just a few minutes ago.

242
00:21:51,799 --> 00:21:54,492
Well, an exhibition like this in Rome...

243
00:21:54,900 --> 00:21:59,628
about an obscure French architect
organized by an American architect...

244
00:22:00,200 --> 00:22:02,597
needs all the publicity it can get.

245
00:22:08,267 --> 00:22:09,596
Wouldn't you say?

246
00:22:19,933 --> 00:22:22,899
I'm gonna go back to the apartment.
I've got some work to do.

247
00:22:22,966 --> 00:22:25,989
Why don't you go sight-seeing?
The Specklers can take you.

248
00:22:26,066 --> 00:22:28,930
God, Stourley! Why don't you take me?

249
00:22:29,000 --> 00:22:32,693
Louisa, please, go with the Specklers.
I'll talk to you later.

250
00:22:33,532 --> 00:22:35,260
Say goodbye for me, okay?

251
00:22:54,100 --> 00:22:55,963
Anything for Boullée.

252
00:25:25,666 --> 00:25:28,098
- Beg your pardon?
- It is closed.

253
00:25:29,066 --> 00:25:31,827
There is nothing much inside anyway.

254
00:25:32,133 --> 00:25:34,122
This is the Tomb of Augustus?

255
00:25:34,233 --> 00:25:36,858
Yes, but he is not at home.

256
00:25:41,666 --> 00:25:44,564
- Louisa, do you like figs?
- Yes.

257
00:25:48,499 --> 00:25:51,522
- I want you to eat a fig for me.
- Not now.

258
00:25:51,599 --> 00:25:52,758
Why not now?

259
00:25:53,367 --> 00:25:55,662
Because it's late and I'm sleeping.

260
00:25:56,432 --> 00:25:57,659
Come on.

261
00:26:00,400 --> 00:26:03,366
Just eat a fig for me.
You can have a little wine afterwards.

262
00:26:03,432 --> 00:26:05,126
- Why?
- Come on.

263
00:26:06,066 --> 00:26:07,656
- Come on, do it for me.
- Stop it.

264
00:26:07,733 --> 00:26:09,131
Take a big bite out of it.

265
00:26:09,200 --> 00:26:11,132
- I don't want one.
- Eat the fig.

266
00:26:13,267 --> 00:26:15,698
- God damn it. Eat it!
- You're hurting me!

267
00:26:18,833 --> 00:26:20,322
Why did you do that?

268
00:26:21,432 --> 00:26:24,399
Okay. All right, I see.

269
00:26:25,633 --> 00:26:26,997
What do you see?

270
00:26:27,933 --> 00:26:31,388
You say you like figs, but you
never touch them, do you? Never.

271
00:26:32,766 --> 00:26:34,232
What is this about?

272
00:26:36,000 --> 00:26:40,126
I just wanted to see what
happened to you if you ate
one of those figs, that's all.

273
00:26:40,200 --> 00:26:41,426
Don't stand there like that.

274
00:26:41,499 --> 00:26:44,261
You'll catch your death of cold.
Get back into bed.

275
00:26:44,400 --> 00:26:45,490
Figs.

276
00:26:47,499 --> 00:26:50,932
They are some kind of aphrodisiac, right?
Is that...

277
00:26:51,000 --> 00:26:54,659
- All right, just forget it!
- No, I'm not gonna forget it.

278
00:26:55,200 --> 00:26:59,132
You come on like a madman
and then you tell me to forget it.

279
00:27:01,033 --> 00:27:02,363
What's wrong with you?

280
00:27:02,432 --> 00:27:05,694
I wanted to see if you're as frightened
of eating those figs as I am.

281
00:27:05,766 --> 00:27:07,027
Are you scared?

282
00:27:07,666 --> 00:27:10,530
Come on, are you scared
to eat those figs? Are you?

283
00:27:12,367 --> 00:27:14,958
Answer me.
Are you frightened to eat those figs?

284
00:27:15,033 --> 00:27:16,397
Answer me!

285
00:27:18,966 --> 00:27:20,761
Why should I be frightened?

286
00:27:25,166 --> 00:27:27,291
I think you ought to see a doctor.

287
00:28:59,333 --> 00:29:00,958
<i>Monday, May 20.</i>

288
00:29:03,267 --> 00:29:05,028
<i>Monsieur Boullée...</i>

289
00:29:06,300 --> 00:29:09,130
<i>I hope you don't mind me</i>
<i>writing to you like this.</i>

290
00:29:11,200 --> 00:29:13,757
<i>I feel I know you well
enough to talk to you.</i>

291
00:29:16,499 --> 00:29:18,727
<i>I think my wife is poisoning me.</i>

292
00:29:22,367 --> 00:29:24,696
<i>You can laugh, but I'm serious.</i>

293
00:29:32,000 --> 00:29:33,966
<i>I'm sure it's part of her...</i>

294
00:29:34,966 --> 00:29:37,761
<i>general animosity towards you.</i>

295
00:29:48,333 --> 00:29:51,890
<i>Yours with respect, Stourley Kracklite.</i>

296
00:29:53,900 --> 00:29:54,991
<i>Architect.</i>

297
00:29:59,699 --> 00:30:03,859
If you are being poisoned, you'd know it.
What are your symptoms?

298
00:30:08,300 --> 00:30:09,890
I've made some notes.

299
00:30:20,432 --> 00:30:22,331
The stomach of Augustus.

300
00:30:23,432 --> 00:30:26,058
Do you have such a heroic abdomen?

301
00:30:26,599 --> 00:30:28,088
Take off your shirt.

302
00:30:34,200 --> 00:30:37,757
- Where does it ache?
- Right about here.

303
00:30:42,166 --> 00:30:43,461
Breathe deeply.

304
00:30:47,766 --> 00:30:49,698
Where did you eat your figs?

305
00:30:49,900 --> 00:30:52,128
At a restaurant opposite the Pantheon.

306
00:30:52,200 --> 00:30:53,597
A fine building.

307
00:30:54,233 --> 00:30:55,823
- Are you married?
- Yes.

308
00:30:55,900 --> 00:30:57,627
Is your wife Italian?

309
00:30:58,000 --> 00:31:00,193
Her parents were Italian, yes.
From Umbria.

310
00:31:00,267 --> 00:31:03,755
A fine fig-growing area.
Do you sleep well at night?

311
00:31:04,466 --> 00:31:06,432
I did before I got to Rome.

312
00:31:06,833 --> 00:31:10,663
Mr. Architect, I can assure you
that you are not being poisoned.

313
00:31:12,466 --> 00:31:16,194
I would suggest that you are
suffering from dyspepsia...

314
00:31:16,267 --> 00:31:18,494
fatigue, over-excitement...

315
00:31:18,633 --> 00:31:21,758
excess and unfamiliar food...

316
00:31:22,133 --> 00:31:25,293
lack of exercise, too much coffee...

317
00:31:25,367 --> 00:31:28,526
and maybe also too much egotism.

318
00:31:34,200 --> 00:31:35,825
Take these...

319
00:31:37,100 --> 00:31:38,963
and obey the instructions.

320
00:31:42,766 --> 00:31:45,255
Is Augustus a hero of yours, Doctor?

321
00:31:45,333 --> 00:31:48,060
Not particularly. He amuses me.

322
00:31:48,666 --> 00:31:50,655
Are you easily amused?

323
00:31:50,933 --> 00:31:53,399
What frame of mind
better suits a doctor?

324
00:32:01,799 --> 00:32:03,526
Where is Kracklite now?

325
00:32:04,367 --> 00:32:08,356
I don't know.
Out marching around Rome somewhere.

326
00:32:08,566 --> 00:32:11,726
He's out when I wake up
and he's asleep when I come in.

327
00:32:12,766 --> 00:32:14,255
What are these?

328
00:32:16,599 --> 00:32:19,827
Something for the exhibition.

329
00:32:19,900 --> 00:32:21,490
No. Look at this.

330
00:32:23,333 --> 00:32:24,662
What is he doing?

331
00:32:25,367 --> 00:32:29,526
- Does he think he's Augustus?
- No. He thinks he's Boullée.

332
00:32:30,633 --> 00:32:33,963
He's obsessed with his stomach.

333
00:32:38,766 --> 00:32:41,755
Maybe he thinks he's
going to have a baby.

334
00:32:44,633 --> 00:32:47,122
When are you going to have a baby?

335
00:32:47,900 --> 00:32:50,991
You could have waited for me downstairs.

336
00:33:17,133 --> 00:33:19,690
You would look very beautiful pregnant.

337
00:33:25,766 --> 00:33:27,629
If I may say so...

338
00:33:28,033 --> 00:33:31,261
since you've been in Rome,
you've put on a little weight.

339
00:33:32,532 --> 00:33:35,965
If you became pregnant,
you would put on even more here.

340
00:33:36,466 --> 00:33:38,955
You seem to know a lot about it.

341
00:33:39,499 --> 00:33:40,931
And here.

342
00:33:41,933 --> 00:33:44,558
You take night classes in obstetrics?

343
00:33:46,166 --> 00:33:48,394
Architects ought to
know about everything:

344
00:33:48,466 --> 00:33:51,058
Reproduction, gender, sex.

345
00:33:51,799 --> 00:33:53,492
Especially sex.

346
00:33:56,833 --> 00:33:59,856
Form, shape...

347
00:34:01,699 --> 00:34:04,756
function, elegance...

348
00:34:05,733 --> 00:34:07,926
Proportionally strong...

349
00:34:09,133 --> 00:34:10,564
enduring...

350
00:34:11,666 --> 00:34:13,189
reliable.

351
00:34:14,367 --> 00:34:16,162
And cost-effective.

352
00:34:18,466 --> 00:34:21,228
You're talking to an architect's wife.

353
00:34:22,233 --> 00:34:25,222
I wish I was talking to
an architect's mistress.

354
00:34:25,833 --> 00:34:28,299
God, Caspasian!

355
00:34:28,900 --> 00:34:31,366
Kracklite was never that forward.

356
00:34:34,599 --> 00:34:37,997
- He was never that talented.
- Or that arrogant.

357
00:34:39,532 --> 00:34:41,725
Still, you've taken your time.

358
00:34:42,133 --> 00:34:43,792
I've been here for 10 weeks.

359
00:34:43,866 --> 00:34:48,196
I would have thought, with
your reputation, you would
have made a move before now.

360
00:34:49,166 --> 00:34:51,654
Maybe I was waiting for a sign from you.

361
00:34:52,200 --> 00:34:54,166
What kind of sign?

362
00:34:55,900 --> 00:34:58,025
Putting on a little more weight...

363
00:34:59,400 --> 00:35:01,127
becoming more Roman.

364
00:35:04,267 --> 00:35:05,698
I've guessed.

365
00:35:06,666 --> 00:35:07,723
What?

366
00:35:12,799 --> 00:35:14,662
It's all right.

367
00:35:14,833 --> 00:35:16,856
Have you told Kracklite?

368
00:35:18,966 --> 00:35:21,023
- No. I haven't.
- Why not?

369
00:35:22,000 --> 00:35:25,330
If you could guess that I was pregnant,
why couldn't he?

370
00:35:42,033 --> 00:35:44,464
<i>July 31. Dear Boullée...</i>

371
00:35:44,966 --> 00:35:48,728
<i>the Italians are catching on at last.</i>
<i>They're actually beginning to like you...</i>

372
00:35:48,799 --> 00:35:51,697
<i>though it doesn't seem</i>
<i>to make them work any faster.</i>

373
00:35:51,766 --> 00:35:54,425
<i>Caspasian has already
spent 400 million</i> lire.

374
00:35:54,499 --> 00:35:56,727
<i>There seems to be very
little to show for it.</i>

375
00:35:56,799 --> 00:35:57,787
Careful.

376
00:35:59,367 --> 00:36:01,958
<i>If we intend to open on your birthday,</i>
<i>as we must...</i>

377
00:36:02,033 --> 00:36:04,965
<i>we have barely six months to go. Six.</i>

378
00:36:05,933 --> 00:36:07,058
<i>Six months.</i>

379
00:36:07,499 --> 00:36:11,023
- Why is it so difficult?
- Difficult?

380
00:36:11,100 --> 00:36:14,294
Everything has got to be debated,
or qualified, or contradicted.

381
00:36:14,367 --> 00:36:16,559
They're not difficult.
You have them excited.

382
00:36:16,633 --> 00:36:20,656
This is the first time the Victor Emmanuel
Building is being used for an exhibition.

383
00:36:20,733 --> 00:36:22,824
- You ought to be grateful.
- Grateful.

384
00:36:22,900 --> 00:36:25,025
Where is Caspasian? He should be here.

385
00:36:25,100 --> 00:36:27,622
- Caspasian's out buying.
- Buying what?

386
00:36:28,033 --> 00:36:30,397
He's having the staircase repainted.

387
00:36:30,666 --> 00:36:33,757
He's ordered 2,000 liters
of blue matte emulsion...

388
00:36:34,100 --> 00:36:35,565
and the same of green.

389
00:36:35,633 --> 00:36:37,792
Blue and green? No.

390
00:36:38,200 --> 00:36:40,893
There's gonna be no blue and no green
in my exhibition.

391
00:36:40,966 --> 00:36:43,898
- Boullée hated those colors.
- How did you discover that?

392
00:36:43,966 --> 00:36:45,431
Caspasian's found...

393
00:36:45,532 --> 00:36:49,487
$25,000 worth of laser equipment.

394
00:36:49,933 --> 00:36:51,331
What the hell for?

395
00:36:51,499 --> 00:36:53,522
He's got a plan to use laser beams...

396
00:36:53,599 --> 00:36:56,622
to join all the buildings in Rome
that influenced Boullée.

397
00:36:56,699 --> 00:36:57,926
Jesus Christ!

398
00:36:58,033 --> 00:37:00,726
He's turning this exhibition
into a goddamn carnival.

399
00:37:00,799 --> 00:37:02,288
He's got no business doing that.

400
00:37:02,367 --> 00:37:04,992
- Don't you think it's a good idea?
- Good idea?

401
00:37:05,300 --> 00:37:07,129
All right. What's the scale?

402
00:37:07,233 --> 00:37:08,630
It's what you asked for.

403
00:37:08,699 --> 00:37:11,165
- Is it centimeters or inches?
- Centimeters.

404
00:37:11,900 --> 00:37:14,457
No self-respecting architect uses inches.

405
00:37:14,532 --> 00:37:16,021
Did Boullée use inches?

406
00:37:16,100 --> 00:37:17,998
He used Boullées.

407
00:37:18,133 --> 00:37:19,462
How long are they?

408
00:37:19,532 --> 00:37:22,055
The distance from the nose to the navel.

409
00:37:22,300 --> 00:37:24,595
His buildings were based
on human anatomy.

410
00:37:24,666 --> 00:37:26,495
He certainly wasn't a prude.

411
00:37:27,866 --> 00:37:30,025
Are you a prude, <i>Signor</i> Kracklite?

412
00:37:30,633 --> 00:37:31,792
Ask my wife.

413
00:37:33,267 --> 00:37:35,324
Ask your son to ask his wife.

414
00:37:42,766 --> 00:37:43,959
Why did you do that?

415
00:37:44,033 --> 00:37:47,397
To prove, if proof were needed,
that you bleed very easily.

416
00:37:47,733 --> 00:37:49,222
No more, no less.

417
00:37:50,200 --> 00:37:53,757
He deserved it,
but it was an unwise show of anger.

418
00:38:09,633 --> 00:38:13,122
It is said that Hadrian,
the man who built all this...

419
00:38:13,566 --> 00:38:16,055
was a man who suffered
from skin disease...

420
00:38:16,166 --> 00:38:18,597
and who needed to keep his skin wet...

421
00:38:18,900 --> 00:38:21,627
to stop him from scratching
himself to pieces.

422
00:38:21,699 --> 00:38:23,256
Hence the baths.

423
00:38:25,166 --> 00:38:28,189
You are talking about Caracalla.
Hadrian was a genius...

424
00:38:28,966 --> 00:38:30,955
Caracalla merely a thug.

425
00:38:31,166 --> 00:38:33,029
Here at the Villa Adriana...

426
00:38:33,100 --> 00:38:35,964
Hadrian created modern architecture.

427
00:38:36,499 --> 00:38:39,897
It is not unlikely we are sitting
in the seventh tepidarium...

428
00:38:40,200 --> 00:38:42,325
in four foot and six inches...

429
00:38:42,400 --> 00:38:45,490
of tepid and most probably dirty water.

430
00:38:45,733 --> 00:38:49,529
It almost certainly would not meet
our contemporary hygiene standards.

431
00:38:49,766 --> 00:38:51,891
I think it looks better as a ruin.

432
00:38:52,200 --> 00:38:55,360
Rome in ruins has had more
influence on architecture...

433
00:38:55,432 --> 00:38:57,762
than it ever would brand-new.

434
00:38:57,833 --> 00:39:00,424
What you can't see, you can imagine.

435
00:39:01,200 --> 00:39:03,995
Sounds like a woman with clothes on.

436
00:39:09,300 --> 00:39:12,561
- Watch out, it might be rabid.
- Don't get hysterical.

437
00:39:12,633 --> 00:39:13,963
It certainly looks ill.

438
00:39:14,033 --> 00:39:17,295
<i>Tuesday, August 6.</i>
<i>Dear Étienne-Louis Boullée...</i>

439
00:39:17,900 --> 00:39:20,991
<i>the pains are returning,</i>
<i>and I can't eat without vomiting.</i>

440
00:39:21,066 --> 00:39:22,759
It ought to be shot.

441
00:39:23,367 --> 00:39:25,764
Would you shoot
anything that looks sick?

442
00:39:26,000 --> 00:39:28,091
What now, Kracklite?

443
00:39:28,166 --> 00:39:31,427
- Are you looking for sympathy?
- Shut up.

444
00:39:36,599 --> 00:39:40,225
<i>If you breathe in and press your finger</i>
<i>just to the right of your navel...</i>

445
00:39:40,300 --> 00:39:42,027
<i>can you feel a hard lump?</i>

446
00:39:43,466 --> 00:39:46,728
<i>Some days it's spherical,</i>
<i>some days it feels like a cube.</i>

447
00:39:48,400 --> 00:39:51,797
<i>Most days it feels</i>
<i>like a sharp-cornered pyramid.</i>

448
00:39:54,000 --> 00:39:56,522
<i>Did the Pharaohs suffer
from stomach cramps?</i>

449
00:39:59,100 --> 00:40:02,032
<i>The Emperor Hadrian
died of a perforated ulcer.</i>

450
00:40:40,033 --> 00:40:44,227
<i>When you're 54, and grateful for</i>
<i>being able to sleep at night...</i>

451
00:40:44,432 --> 00:40:47,228
<i>eat badly, and pee like a fire engine...</i>

452
00:40:49,133 --> 00:40:53,088
<i>what do you do if you suspect your wife</i>
<i>no longer cares for your company?</i>

453
00:40:53,300 --> 00:40:54,629
<i>I'm sorry, Étienne.</i>

454
00:40:54,699 --> 00:40:57,722
<i>Since you never had a wife,</i>
<i>it was never your problem.</i>

455
00:41:32,466 --> 00:41:35,489
All right, Kracklite, what are you doing?

456
00:41:40,400 --> 00:41:41,729
I'm drowning.

457
00:42:20,966 --> 00:42:22,693
It's no good.

458
00:42:27,666 --> 00:42:29,825
Your body just won't let you do it!

459
00:42:33,633 --> 00:42:36,997
Nobody ever died by
voluntarily ceasing to breathe.

460
00:42:40,432 --> 00:42:43,694
If you managed to stop breathing,
you'd fall unconscious...

461
00:42:44,333 --> 00:42:47,197
and then your goddamn
body starts to breathe again.

462
00:42:47,267 --> 00:42:49,256
Since you're in the bath...

463
00:42:50,200 --> 00:42:52,427
why not try slitting your wrists?

464
00:42:53,699 --> 00:42:56,029
That is very appropriate for Rome.

465
00:42:56,300 --> 00:42:59,595
You'll have to wait a minute
because I'm using your razor.

466
00:42:59,733 --> 00:43:01,756
Livia was very hairy, too.

467
00:43:02,233 --> 00:43:03,858
Who's Livia?

468
00:43:05,499 --> 00:43:07,431
Augustus' wife.

469
00:43:12,933 --> 00:43:14,899
How do you know she was hairy?

470
00:43:15,033 --> 00:43:16,896
She left hair in the bath.

471
00:43:16,966 --> 00:43:19,830
It's in Caesar's <i>Gallic Wars</i> in Book Five.

472
00:43:20,532 --> 00:43:24,397
- She tried to kill her husband.
- With his razor?

473
00:43:26,000 --> 00:43:29,296
No, with figs. Poisoned figs.

474
00:43:32,633 --> 00:43:34,758
Augustus fell for it, too.

475
00:43:35,333 --> 00:43:37,423
At least, according to Robert Graves.

476
00:43:37,499 --> 00:43:39,795
Who's he? Another architect?

477
00:43:43,900 --> 00:43:47,593
No.
Robert Graves is a mortuary attendant.

478
00:43:49,799 --> 00:43:52,629
- Where are you going?
- Out to dinner.

479
00:43:54,333 --> 00:43:56,855
Caspasian and Flavia have invited me.

480
00:43:58,333 --> 00:43:59,958
Why didn't they ask me?

481
00:44:00,466 --> 00:44:02,399
You can come, if you like.

482
00:44:04,166 --> 00:44:06,257
They didn't ask me personally.

483
00:44:09,966 --> 00:44:13,864
I expect it's because you're so fussy
about your food.

484
00:44:14,766 --> 00:44:17,926
Caspasian can't stand vegetarians.

485
00:44:18,166 --> 00:44:20,291
All fascists are meat-eaters.

486
00:44:21,866 --> 00:44:24,298
- That's funny.
- What's funny?

487
00:44:26,100 --> 00:44:29,191
Because that's what he said about you.

488
00:44:29,699 --> 00:44:31,688
What, that I'm a fascist?

489
00:44:33,133 --> 00:44:35,122
That's ironic, coming from him.

490
00:44:39,033 --> 00:44:41,555
You look good. You look very good.

491
00:44:42,033 --> 00:44:45,056
In fact, you look so good,
I wouldn't be surprised...

492
00:44:45,766 --> 00:44:48,698
if you were going out
with Caspasian alone.

493
00:44:49,133 --> 00:44:50,792
