printer's next Tuesday.

573
00:53:05,833 --> 00:53:08,628
There are still major problems
with the color reproduction.

574
00:53:08,699 --> 00:53:12,461
The main gallery hasn't been started
due to the hold-up on the Newton model.

575
00:53:12,532 --> 00:53:15,397
And of course we have to pay
the electricians to stand by...

576
00:53:15,466 --> 00:53:17,228
otherwise we'll lose them.

577
00:53:26,100 --> 00:53:29,463
- Do you feel any better?
- No.

578
00:53:31,466 --> 00:53:33,557
They tell me it's constipation.

579
00:53:34,866 --> 00:53:37,832
But it's gone on far too long
for it to be just that.

580
00:53:38,532 --> 00:53:42,295
- We could delay the opening date.
- No, that's just what we cannot do.

581
00:53:43,666 --> 00:53:47,928
Then offload some of your responsibility.
Give it to Caspasian.

582
00:53:49,267 --> 00:53:51,698
He can take care of the
details for a few weeks.

583
00:53:51,766 --> 00:53:54,028
Yeah, that's just what I'm afraid of.

584
00:53:54,966 --> 00:53:57,989
- He's capable enough.
- No.

585
00:54:00,566 --> 00:54:03,532
Caspasian has taken over
too much of my life already.

586
00:54:25,966 --> 00:54:28,693
Do you mind if I ask you
a personal question?

587
00:54:29,367 --> 00:54:30,355
Go on.

588
00:54:33,733 --> 00:54:35,665
Why did you divorce your wife?

589
00:54:37,400 --> 00:54:38,695
Jealousy.

590
00:54:39,100 --> 00:54:42,191
I suspected her of having an affair.

591
00:54:44,133 --> 00:54:46,792
And were your suspicions well-founded?

592
00:54:48,432 --> 00:54:51,126
I thought so at the time.
Now I'm not so sure.

593
00:54:51,766 --> 00:54:52,993
I think, in fact...

594
00:54:53,066 --> 00:54:56,362
that the man was after my daughter,
Flavia, not my wife.

595
00:54:57,666 --> 00:54:59,326
But the damage was done.

596
00:54:59,400 --> 00:55:02,559
Too much had been said,
too much vengeance taken.

597
00:55:04,966 --> 00:55:08,262
Look, Kracklite,
if you won't take time off...

598
00:55:08,666 --> 00:55:10,427
at least come to the baths.

599
00:55:11,066 --> 00:55:12,463
It'll do you good.

600
00:55:13,100 --> 00:55:14,998
When things slacken off later.

601
00:55:16,000 --> 00:55:18,522
Now I just want to go
home and try to sleep.

602
00:55:54,833 --> 00:55:56,231
Hello, Joe.

603
00:57:29,933 --> 00:57:31,399
Why are you crying?

604
00:57:34,066 --> 00:57:36,157
I'm crying because there's a draft...

605
00:57:36,233 --> 00:57:39,063
through the keyhole.
It hits me in the eye.

606
00:57:42,432 --> 00:57:44,557
He's got a draft in his eye.

607
00:59:48,766 --> 00:59:51,130
<i>Thursday, August 22.</i>

608
00:59:51,799 --> 00:59:53,628
<i>Dear Étienne-Louis...</i>

609
00:59:54,833 --> 00:59:57,458
<i>I wonder why you never came to Rome?</i>

610
00:59:59,599 --> 01:00:01,724
<i>Did traveling make you ill?</i>

611
01:00:03,300 --> 01:00:05,765
<i>Were you suspicious of foreigners?</i>

612
01:00:10,966 --> 01:00:13,057
<i>Did you ever eat an orange?</i>

613
01:00:20,566 --> 01:00:23,192
<i>Did you even know what vitamin C was?</i>

614
01:00:23,933 --> 01:00:26,399
<i>It's supposed to make you healthy.</i>

615
01:01:26,532 --> 01:01:28,964
I'm sorry, I don't speak Italian.

616
01:01:29,100 --> 01:01:30,725
Mind if I watch?

617
01:01:56,100 --> 01:02:00,623
<i>Étienne-Louis, what was the current</i>
<i>stomach complaint when you were alive?</i>

618
01:02:01,000 --> 01:02:04,432
<i>Gallstones? Kidney stones? Appendicitis?</i>

619
01:02:05,666 --> 01:02:07,495
<i>Pancreatic carcinoma?</i>

620
01:02:49,400 --> 01:02:52,389
<i>Signor</i> Kracklite, do you dream?

621
01:02:53,267 --> 01:02:54,255
Yes.

622
01:02:54,799 --> 01:02:56,628
What do you dream of?

623
01:02:58,000 --> 01:02:59,556
Lately, stairs.

624
01:03:00,599 --> 01:03:02,724
I'm always climbing stairs.

625
01:03:04,133 --> 01:03:06,065
Or falling down stairs.

626
01:03:06,900 --> 01:03:08,923
A sure sign of dyspepsia.

627
01:03:10,200 --> 01:03:12,359
No, I don't believe that anymore.

628
01:03:12,532 --> 01:03:15,464
Then what do you believe?

629
01:03:21,000 --> 01:03:22,863
Boullée died of cancer.

630
01:03:23,900 --> 01:03:26,491
Your respect for the man, Kracklite...

631
01:03:26,566 --> 01:03:29,691
does not imply that you
have to suffer his injuries.

632
01:03:45,799 --> 01:03:48,492
<i>Monsieur</i> Boullée was a
French hypochondriac.

633
01:03:48,566 --> 01:03:50,623
- Did you know that?
- No.

634
01:03:52,200 --> 01:03:56,461
- He was a little lame.
Are you a little lame? - No.

635
01:03:56,900 --> 01:03:58,923
He suffered from gout.

636
01:03:59,333 --> 01:04:01,662
He was afraid of thunderstorms.

637
01:04:02,233 --> 01:04:04,290
They made him incontinent.

638
01:04:05,766 --> 01:04:07,823
You seem very well-informed.

639
01:04:07,900 --> 01:04:12,162
Why do you think he built so little?
Why do you think he traveled so little?

640
01:04:12,367 --> 01:04:14,628
His illness incapacitated him.

641
01:04:14,766 --> 01:04:18,028
He stayed at home for fear
of embarrassment abroad.

642
01:04:18,799 --> 01:04:20,458
Look, Kracklite...

643
01:04:20,900 --> 01:04:23,093
