739
01:16:37,733 --> 01:16:41,859
that what is good for the goose,
is good for the philanderer.

740
01:16:42,000 --> 01:16:43,932
An English proverb?

741
01:16:44,033 --> 01:16:47,022
Philanderer?
That's very funny coming from you.

742
01:16:47,100 --> 01:16:49,657
Your wife is very beautiful,
<i>Signor</i> Kracklite...

743
01:16:49,733 --> 01:16:51,290
especially when she is pregnant.

744
01:16:51,367 --> 01:16:55,163
Yes, that's right. She is pregnant.
But not with your child, Speckler.

745
01:16:55,233 --> 01:16:58,290
True. I'm very grateful to you for that.

746
01:16:59,233 --> 01:17:02,256
Your child, shall we say...

747
01:17:02,466 --> 01:17:05,591
is the most perfect contraceptive.

748
01:17:20,133 --> 01:17:22,655
Don't get your blood on my white towel.

749
01:17:31,466 --> 01:17:34,331
I take it that you will now give Louisa...

750
01:17:34,400 --> 01:17:36,422
as much freedom as
you've taken yourself.

751
01:17:36,499 --> 01:17:39,590
One hardly can give what
has already been taken.

752
01:17:39,699 --> 01:17:42,927
Nonetheless, I'm sure you
don't want her to know.

753
01:17:45,699 --> 01:17:49,688
There are enough stomachs here
to have many illnesses.

754
01:17:49,766 --> 01:17:52,198
What about the ones in the camera?

755
01:17:52,933 --> 01:17:54,058
Well?

756
01:17:55,033 --> 01:17:57,521
So how is the exhibition progressing?

757
01:17:57,599 --> 01:17:59,656
Are you still in full control of things?

758
01:17:59,733 --> 01:18:03,597
Don't you think you should hand
over the reins to somebody else?

759
01:18:03,733 --> 01:18:05,222
Is that what this is?

760
01:18:05,300 --> 01:18:07,993
This is a setup?
You're trying to blackmail me?

761
01:18:08,066 --> 01:18:10,362
You think I would turn over
the exhibition to you...

762
01:18:10,432 --> 01:18:13,399
just to keep my wife from knowing
I tried to screw your sister?

763
01:18:13,466 --> 01:18:15,932
Thank you, Stourley, for the compliment.

764
01:18:16,000 --> 01:18:19,864
But don't worry. Caspasian is
always overreaching himself.

765
01:18:20,599 --> 01:18:23,531
If you want a really serious quarrel...

766
01:18:24,033 --> 01:18:27,430
I'm sorry,
but there is no film in the camera.

767
01:18:46,432 --> 01:18:48,728
Well, we've done it. Kracklite is finished.

768
01:18:48,799 --> 01:18:51,391
He's looking a mess. He's grotesque.

769
01:18:51,466 --> 01:18:53,830
Trettorio says he won't last till August.

770
01:18:53,900 --> 01:18:57,593
And I've got another 16 million
from the publicity account.

771
01:18:57,666 --> 01:18:59,655
And the cupola will never be finished...

772
01:18:59,733 --> 01:19:02,893
because Kracklite says
he wants the olden color.

773
01:19:03,766 --> 01:19:06,994
"My architect Boullée
knew more about color...

774
01:19:07,066 --> 01:19:09,123
than Leonardo da Vinci.

775
01:19:09,300 --> 01:19:12,993
And more about publicity
than Michelangelo Buonarroti.

776
01:19:13,066 --> 01:19:15,861
And more about making
love than Casanova."

777
01:19:32,966 --> 01:19:35,761
Kracklite, we've got to see you.

778
01:19:35,833 --> 01:19:38,061
The bank has stopped the cash flow.

779
01:19:38,933 --> 01:19:41,922
It looks as though the
bankers have found out...

780
01:19:42,000 --> 01:19:43,659
that you are a sick man.

781
01:19:44,100 --> 01:19:46,157
They want you to have
a medical examination.

782
01:19:46,233 --> 01:19:48,165
I'm not a sick man!

783
01:19:48,432 --> 01:19:49,557
I just had one.

784
01:19:49,633 --> 01:19:51,496
Caspetti has asked...

785
01:19:51,566 --> 01:19:55,363
that Caspasian should be made
the director of the exhibition.

786
01:19:55,900 --> 01:19:57,127
He what?

787
01:19:57,200 --> 01:20:01,155
He thinks that the
exhibition is too academic.

788
01:20:01,900 --> 01:20:04,764
He thinks you've got too
many domestic problems.

789
01:20:05,900 --> 01:20:08,627
What the hell has that
got to do with anything?

790
01:20:08,799 --> 01:20:11,629
He thinks that Caspasian
will give the exhibition...

791
01:20:11,699 --> 01:20:14,131
a more Roman and optimistic bias.

792
01:20:14,866 --> 01:20:17,128
Optimistic.
Is that what the laser beams are for?

793
01:20:17,200 --> 01:20:18,790
Caspasian's optimism?

794
01:20:18,866 --> 01:20:20,559
Over my dead body!

795
01:20:21,100 --> 01:20:22,861
Not a bad prognosis.

796
01:20:22,933 --> 01:20:24,728
What was that? What?

797
01:20:25,499 --> 01:20:29,159
- I'm just as healthy as you are.
- Stourley, you know that's not true.

798
01:20:29,966 --> 01:20:32,864
Are you going to punch
me on the nose again?

799
01:20:35,799 --> 01:20:37,765
Your friend, Caspetti...

800
01:20:38,532 --> 01:20:41,328
he was against Boullée
right from the start.

801
01:20:41,499 --> 01:20:44,693
Said he reminded him of Hell.
I'll give him hell.

802
01:20:50,033 --> 01:20:53,487
Kracklite, I'm afraid that
they've put up an ultimatum.

803
01:20:54,267 --> 01:20:57,630
We need another 300 million <i>lire.</i>

804
01:20:58,033 --> 01:21:00,794
But the bank thinks you are unreliable.

805
01:21:02,300 --> 01:21:05,754
You have to resign
if you want the exhibition to go on.

806
01:21:05,900 --> 01:21:08,093
We can't let it collapse now.

807
01:21:08,566 --> 01:21:10,657
You're damn right we can't.

808
01:21:10,933 --> 01:21:13,455
Let Caspetti believe
Caspasian is in charge.

809
01:21:13,532 --> 01:21:14,589
No!

810
01:21:14,799 --> 01:21:18,095
- No, I can't do that.
- Stourley, I don't think we have a choice.

811
01:21:18,166 --> 01:21:20,155
Look, I'll think of something.

812
01:21:20,233 --> 01:21:23,721
Don't be absurd. We open in 12 days.

813
01:21:24,233 --> 01:21:26,721
Where the hell is Caspasian anyway?

814
01:21:27,233 --> 01:21:28,960
He should be here to deal with this.

815
01:21:29,033 --> 01:21:31,828
He's the one who's been
spending all the goddamn money.

816
01:21:32,466 --> 01:21:36,399
Yeah, he's been behind this all along.
That bastard son of yours.

817
01:21:36,499 --> 01:21:39,988
He's determined to get his hands on
this exhibition right from the start.

818
01:21:40,066 --> 01:21:42,725
- Where is he?
- He's not here. He's out.

819
01:21:43,200 --> 01:21:45,257
He's out? He's out where?

820
01:21:45,699 --> 01:21:47,256
Raising funds.

821
01:21:49,933 --> 01:21:52,399
I'll bet he's not raising funds for Boullée.

822
01:21:52,466 --> 01:21:54,898
- You're right.
- Then what for?

823
01:21:55,466 --> 01:21:58,432
- Some restoration work.
- Where? Doing what?

824
01:21:58,933 --> 01:22:01,195
Restoring Mussolini's Foro Italica.

825
01:22:05,566 --> 01:22:08,294
So that's where all the
money has been going?

826
01:22:09,599 --> 01:22:12,656
I've been subsidizing that
goddamn fascist playground!

827
01:22:12,933 --> 01:22:15,229
Kracklite, you can't say that.

828
01:22:16,133 --> 01:22:18,690
And you certainly couldn't prove it.

829
01:22:22,466 --> 01:22:25,024
Don't you think Boullée would have been
the first to applauded...

830
01:22:25,100 --> 01:22:28,497
such a visionary piece
of architectural theater?

831
01:22:30,466 --> 01:22:33,455
Why isn't Caspasian
raising money for Boullée?

832
01:22:37,200 --> 01:22:39,223
Look. Take a look.

833
01:22:40,200 --> 01:22:44,632
If they could do it to Battistino,
one of their own, they could do it to me.

834
01:22:45,833 --> 01:22:47,560
And I'm not faking.

835
01:22:48,733 --> 01:22:51,393
- So you admit you're ill?
- Ill?

836
01:22:52,633 --> 01:22:54,895
Christ, I'm sick as a dog.

837
01:22:58,666 --> 01:23:01,461
But I'm still tough enough to take you on.

838
01:23:01,532 --> 01:23:04,896
And Pastarri! And Caspetti!

839
01:23:05,000 --> 01:23:07,625
And Caspasian, and all the rest of you.

840
01:23:09,532 --> 01:23:11,294
I'll get that money.

841
01:23:12,933 --> 01:23:16,161
I'll get that goddamn money,
if I have to steal it.

842
01:24:45,966 --> 01:24:49,591
- Where the hell have you been?
- Wouldn't you like to know?

843
01:24:50,100 --> 01:24:51,656
As if you cared.

844
01:24:52,300 --> 01:24:55,493
That's all right,
we'll keep it all in the family.

845
01:24:55,566 --> 01:24:57,555
What is that supposed to mean?

846
01:24:57,633 --> 01:25:00,565
It means that we've
seen the same doctor...

847
01:25:00,633 --> 01:25:03,827
and the same photographer, haven't we?

848
01:25:04,267 --> 01:25:06,630
And not with the same complaint.

849
01:25:06,900 --> 01:25:10,798
Though you might as well.
Your stomach's almost as big as mine.

850
01:25:13,300 --> 01:25:15,198
I made some decisions.

851
01:25:18,033 --> 01:25:20,555
I'm gonna mortgage
the house in Chicago.

852
01:25:20,633 --> 01:25:23,099
Oh, really? What for?

853
01:25:23,866 --> 01:25:25,389
It's my house.

854
01:25:25,933 --> 01:25:28,490
You built it for me, don't you remember?

855
01:25:28,833 --> 01:25:31,061
With its wide-open, drafty spaces...

856
01:25:31,133 --> 01:25:34,496
and its rounded corners
where you can't fit any furniture.

857
01:25:34,566 --> 01:25:37,124
I'm gonna change the
beneficiaries of the trust fund.

858
01:25:37,200 --> 01:25:41,132
- Oh, no, you don't.
- I need $200,000 right away.

859
01:25:42,133 --> 01:25:45,224
Caspasian could get that sort of money
by snapping his fingers.

860
01:25:45,300 --> 01:25:46,890
Snapping his fingers?

861
01:25:49,432 --> 01:25:51,262
I'd like to snap his neck.

862
01:25:51,333 --> 01:25:53,924
He's snapped you up very quickly,
hasn't he?

863
01:25:54,000 --> 01:25:57,023
Well, he's not gonna
snap up my exhibition.

864
01:25:57,100 --> 01:25:59,293
I'll tell you something else.

865
01:25:59,532 --> 01:26:02,158
- I'm gonna change my will.
- What will?

866
01:26:03,066 --> 01:26:06,520
I refuse to let my exhibition
slip through my fingers...

867
01:26:06,599 --> 01:26:08,395
if it's the last thing I ever do.

868
01:26:08,466 --> 01:26:11,160
And it will be, the way that you're going.

869
01:26:11,233 --> 01:26:13,630
You're not gonna ruin my child's future...

870
01:26:13,699 --> 01:26:17,359
for the sake of another
unfinished Kracklite fiasco.

871
01:26:17,432 --> 01:26:18,796
Our child!

872
01:26:20,699 --> 01:26:22,858
Or do you even care who the father is?

873
01:26:22,933 --> 01:26:24,762
- No!
- No, of course not!

874
01:26:24,833 --> 01:26:29,391
I'll tell you something else.
Our child is gonna be born in America.

875
01:26:29,833 --> 01:26:31,094
He is?

876
01:26:35,799 --> 01:26:38,265
As soon as this exhibition is opened...

877
01:26:38,833 --> 01:26:41,356
- we're going home.
- We are?

878
01:26:42,633 --> 01:26:46,066
I like the idea of him being born in Italy.

879
01:26:46,432 --> 01:26:48,921
I think I'll call him Luigi.

880
01:26:49,000 --> 01:26:51,864
I was sure you were
gonna call him Caspasian.

881
01:26:51,933 --> 01:26:53,899
What makes you think it's a boy?

882
01:26:53,966 --> 01:26:55,829
By the shape of my stomach...

883
01:26:55,900 --> 01:26:58,695
that you haven't even looked at
in the last four months.

884
01:26:58,766 --> 01:27:01,392
And who told you that?
Let me see if I can guess.

885
01:27:01,466 --> 01:27:05,762
That great medical architect,
Caspasian Speckler.

886
01:27:06,599 --> 01:27:08,963
As a matter of fact, his sister.

887
01:27:09,233 --> 01:27:12,665
His sister? All the Specklers
have studied gynecology?

888
01:27:13,267 --> 01:27:17,359
You're the one with the
obsessional interest in stomachs.

889
01:27:18,000 --> 01:27:19,898
Masculine stomachs.

890
01:27:21,300 --> 01:27:24,164
Are you going off women completely?

891
01:27:24,633 --> 01:27:28,895
Well, if you have, here's something
to remind you what they look like!

892
01:27:33,133 --> 01:27:34,258
This is awful.

893
01:27:35,966 --> 01:27:38,194
- These are obscene!
- Are they?

894
01:27:38,267 --> 01:27:40,926
Jesus, displaying yourself like this!

895
01:27:41,300 --> 01:27:43,289
It's for art, Kracklite.

896
01:27:43,400 --> 01:27:45,991
Everything's permissible for art.

897
01:27:46,233 --> 01:27:47,823
Look at our marriage:

898
01:27:47,900 --> 01:27:50,923
Art first, Kracklite second...

899
01:27:51,000 --> 01:27:53,465
and the rest a long way down the line.

900
01:27:54,166 --> 01:27:56,064
That's my child in here.

901
01:27:56,233 --> 01:27:59,028
Oh, right.
That's the heart of the matter.

902
01:27:59,933 --> 01:28:03,660
Do you really think
you have the right to feel prostituted?

903
01:28:06,233 --> 01:28:08,256
Look, I'm due in a month...

904
01:28:08,466 --> 01:28:10,932
the exhibition opens in 12 days...

905
01:28:11,466 --> 01:28:13,399
and you're unreliable.

906
01:28:14,166 --> 01:28:17,654
I have no intention of losing this child...

907
01:28:18,200 --> 01:28:20,495
or of dropping it too soon.

908
01:28:22,267 --> 01:28:24,698
And I'd like it to have a future.

909
01:28:27,200 --> 01:28:28,756
I'm moving out.

910
01:28:33,900 --> 01:28:35,695
Where are you going?

911
01:28:37,166 --> 01:28:40,495
As if it's any of your business,
which I doubt...

912
01:28:42,000 --> 01:28:44,431
I'm going to stay with Caspasian.

913
01:28:45,133 --> 01:28:48,895
He'll take care of me
until after the baby is born.

914
01:28:51,633 --> 01:28:53,599
After that, I don't know.

915
01:28:56,666 --> 01:28:59,894
Please, don't leave me now. Please.

916
01:29:02,833 --> 01:29:05,628
It's too late for that, Stourley.

917
01:29:10,200 --> 01:29:11,495
I said...

918
01:29:12,367 --> 01:29:14,958
I just don't need you anymore.

919
01:29:59,933 --> 01:30:03,421
Whatever the results of the
medical examinations...

920
01:30:03,666 --> 01:30:06,894
everyone feels that you
can do no more for Boullée.

921
01:30:07,666 --> 01:30:09,394
He's in safe hands.

922
01:30:13,766 --> 01:30:17,459
I'm sorry, Kracklite. Very sorry.

923
01:30:18,499 --> 01:30:21,659
But you've got to accept that you've lost.

924
01:30:24,133 --> 01:30:27,031
The exhibition is not yours anymore.

925
01:30:28,432 --> 01:30:30,228
You've got to retire.

926
01:30:32,133 --> 01:30:33,496
Gracefully.

927
01:30:34,733 --> 01:30:37,927
Of course,
we would like you to open the exhibition.

928
01:30:38,000 --> 01:30:42,160
And then you must leave the running
of the exhibition to Caspasian.

929
01:30:43,499 --> 01:30:44,658
To us.

930
01:30:48,066 --> 01:30:51,396
After the opening,
why don't you go back to Chicago...

931
01:30:51,766 --> 01:30:53,994
and take a well-deserved rest?

932
01:30:57,733 --> 01:30:59,596
Shall I wait for you?

933
01:31:06,699 --> 01:31:08,597
<i>Monday, February 10.</i>

934
01:31:09,432 --> 01:31:11,262
<i>Dear Étienne-Louis...</i>

935
01:31:16,333 --> 01:31:19,060
<i>It's no good, Étienne. I've been fired.</i>

936
01:31:21,233 --> 01:31:25,824
<i>I've been kicked out of the</i>
<i>exhibition I spent the last</i>
<i>10 years of my life planning.</i>

937
01:31:27,766 --> 01:31:29,323
<i>It's Caspasian's fault.</i>

938
01:31:29,400 --> 01:31:32,264
<i>He's run off with my wife, my child...</i>

939
01:31:32,799 --> 01:31:34,390
<i>our exhibition.</i>

940
01:31:34,466 --> 01:31:36,160
<i>But I've got an idea!</i>

941
01:31:38,532 --> 01:31:40,760
<i>Suppose you came to
open the exhibition.</i>

942
01:31:40,833 --> 01:31:43,197
<i>Why don't you come
and open it with me?</i>

943
01:31:43,333 --> 01:31:45,594
<i>How about that?</i>
<i>That would show them.</i>

944
01:31:51,599 --> 01:31:53,293
<i>You could stay in my apartment.</i>

945
01:31:53,367 --> 01:31:56,594
<i>Louisa's not there anymore.</i>
<i>I don't sleep too well...</i>

946
01:31:58,599 --> 01:32:00,792
<i>but I'm sure we could manage.</i>

947
01:32:16,367 --> 01:32:18,162
<i>Yours with respect...</i>

948
01:32:19,000 --> 01:32:20,522
<i>Stourley Kracklite.</i>

949
01:32:24,432 --> 01:32:25,762
<i>Architect.</i>

950
01:32:31,900 --> 01:32:32,888
Galba.

951
01:32:34,267 --> 01:32:38,097
He was a miserable sort of man.
Bisexual, fancied mature slaves.

952
01:32:38,166 --> 01:32:41,189
Especially if they had
been a little mutilated.

953
01:32:41,267 --> 01:32:44,562
All his freed men had no fingers
on their left hand.

954
01:32:45,200 --> 01:32:47,257
He's dead. Died screaming.

955
01:32:50,300 --> 01:32:51,492
Titus.

956
01:32:52,100 --> 01:32:55,328
Started off well enough.
Soon became greedy.

957
01:32:55,966 --> 01:32:58,296
Disemboweled on the Tiber steps.

958
01:32:59,599 --> 01:33:01,622
He's dead. Died screaming.

959
01:33:04,766 --> 01:33:06,027
Hadrian.

960
01:33:06,432 --> 01:33:11,092
As you know, an architect of some
repute. He put a lot of faith in stones.

961
01:33:12,432 --> 01:33:15,523
He died peacefully,
planning a temple to Wisdom.

962
01:33:16,333 --> 01:33:17,923
Still, he's dead.

963
01:33:23,599 --> 01:33:26,259
Nero. It's best not to talk about him.

964
01:33:27,566 --> 01:33:31,055
He caused untold damage, burnt Rome.

965
01:33:32,267 --> 01:33:34,028
He deserved to die.

966
01:33:35,367 --> 01:33:37,855
He died screaming in a summerhouse.

967
01:33:43,200 --> 01:33:45,563
And he's unknown. No name.

968
01:33:46,833 --> 01:33:49,061
Still, he looks serene enough.

969
01:33:49,733 --> 01:33:51,494
Let's suppose he was you.

970
01:33:51,566 --> 01:33:54,192
Same fleshy face.
What happened to him?

971
01:33:54,400 --> 01:33:55,956
How did he die?

972
01:33:59,267 --> 01:34:00,789
He died alone...

973
01:34:01,000 --> 01:34:04,488
at noon, in a parked car
on Lakeshore Drive in Chicago.

974
01:34:06,400 --> 01:34:09,490
Stock-market report
playing on the car radio.

975
01:34:10,300 --> 01:34:12,925
He had shaved off his beard...

976
01:34:14,066 --> 01:34:16,497
he was wearing an English suit...

977
01:34:17,367 --> 01:34:19,060
and Italian shoes.

978
01:34:19,466 --> 01:34:22,523
- Is that what you want?
- Is that what I want?

979
01:34:25,900 --> 01:34:27,490
No.

980
01:34:28,733 --> 01:34:33,029
No, he died much later, aged 71.
Same age as Boullée.

981
01:34:34,833 --> 01:34:38,266
He was sitting in a garden
at 4:00 in the afternoon...

982
01:34:38,699 --> 01:34:40,256
facing south.

983
01:34:42,233 --> 01:34:43,721
Somewhere near Rome.

984
01:34:46,100 --> 01:34:48,588
He could hear the sound of water.

985
01:34:50,933 --> 01:34:53,956
His 6-year-old grandson
playing in the gravel.

986
01:34:56,466 --> 01:34:57,864
His wife...

987
01:35:01,532 --> 01:35:03,192
His second wife...

988
01:35:04,566 --> 01:35:06,555
picking orange blossoms.

989
01:35:08,267 --> 01:35:10,789
A little sentimental, no?

990
01:35:12,599 --> 01:35:16,157
What the hell, when you're 71,
you can afford a little sentiment.

991
01:35:16,233 --> 01:35:17,755
Far from home?

992
01:35:18,432 --> 01:35:19,523
Home?

993
01:35:22,633 --> 01:35:25,327
A home should be no particular problem.

994
01:35:26,633 --> 01:35:30,497
- A sort of late spring death?
- You prefer a late spring?

995
01:36:05,166 --> 01:36:07,155
How far into late spring?

996
01:36:09,000 --> 01:36:10,898
Maybe last week of May.

997
01:36:11,200 --> 01:36:13,098
The first week of June.

998
01:36:17,466 --> 01:36:18,557
June.

999
01:36:38,267 --> 01:36:38,900
Tell me, Doctor, do you...

1000
01:36:38,900 --> 01:36:40,332
Tell me, Doctor, do you...

1001
01:36:41,432 --> 01:36:44,228
take this trouble with all your patients?

1002
01:36:44,799 --> 01:36:47,322
I must admit, it's not the first time.

1003
01:36:47,400 --> 01:36:51,729
Though, in another case, the details
may not be quite so architectural.

1004
01:36:53,966 --> 01:36:57,921
Still, you must admit, there is some
comfort to be had in contemplating...

1005
01:36:58,000 --> 01:37:00,932
the folly of so many dead,
don't you think?

1006
01:37:02,532 --> 01:37:05,987
And more comfort still in
contemplating the continuity.

1007
01:37:12,066 --> 01:37:13,396
Thank you.

1008
01:39:21,233 --> 01:39:22,392
Sorry.

1009
01:39:30,400 --> 01:39:32,831
There's not much elbow room here.

1010
01:39:37,966 --> 01:39:40,091
What happened to this place?

1011
01:39:40,432 --> 01:39:42,092
Where is my sign?

1012
01:39:46,900 --> 01:39:48,196
Here you are.

1013
01:39:48,900 --> 01:39:51,389
- You all right?
- No.

1014
01:39:51,566 --> 01:39:55,828
I wouldn't eat those
figs if I were you, lady.

1015
01:39:57,766 --> 01:40:01,698
They're aphrodisiacs. You don't look
like you're up to it to me, I'm sorry.

1016
01:40:01,766 --> 01:40:03,232
Okay, I'm sorry.

1017
01:40:04,733 --> 01:40:07,893
What are you calling him for?
He's not gonna do you any good.

1018
01:40:07,966 --> 01:40:10,023
Go on. No, wait.

1019
01:40:10,100 --> 01:40:12,225
I'm gonna sit down...

1020
01:40:12,333 --> 01:40:14,322
and I'm gonna have dinner here, okay?

1021
01:40:14,400 --> 01:40:18,264
'Cause, see,
my doctor says I should eat in company.

1022
01:40:18,333 --> 01:40:20,628
See? I have to eat in company.

1023
01:40:21,333 --> 01:40:23,798
My wife wants to eat in
company all the time.

1024
01:40:23,866 --> 01:40:26,525
In fact, my wife likes to eat company.

1025
01:40:27,633 --> 01:40:29,861
I like to eat company, too.

1026
01:40:31,966 --> 01:40:34,159
We're all the same, aren't we?

1027
01:40:34,733 --> 01:40:36,699
Come on, we're all the same.

1028
01:40:36,766 --> 01:40:41,222
We speak a different language,
but we have the same metabolism!

1029
01:40:43,100 --> 01:40:45,089
See, the difference is...

1030
01:40:45,799 --> 01:40:48,197
I'm interested in bellies.

1031
01:40:48,566 --> 01:40:51,657
Say, you have a belly.
There's your belly, right there, see?

1032
01:40:51,733 --> 01:40:55,063
I'm sorry. All right, I'll say "stomach."

1033
01:40:57,166 --> 01:40:59,189
"Stomach" in mixed company.

1034
01:41:03,733 --> 01:41:05,790
Come here. Come over here.

1035
01:41:05,866 --> 01:41:09,889
You have a belly, too. Here, see?
You got a belly. See?

1036
01:41:10,367 --> 01:41:12,162
I got a belly. I'll tell you what.

1037
01:41:12,233 --> 01:41:15,858
I'll show you mine, if you show me yours.
Here's mine.

1038
01:41:16,566 --> 01:41:18,328
There's mine, okay?

1039
01:41:20,499 --> 01:41:23,091
It's the same as yours,
a little larger than yours.

1040
01:41:23,166 --> 01:41:25,132
See, the difference is...

1041
01:41:25,300 --> 01:41:27,857
mine is being eaten away.

1042
01:41:28,133 --> 01:41:32,088
Mine is rotting away from the inside.
You understand what I'm saying?

1043
01:41:33,233 --> 01:41:36,256
No! I'm talking to the lady here.

1044
01:41:36,566 --> 01:41:38,930
Here, put your hand out.
Come on, touch it.

1045
01:41:39,000 --> 01:41:43,023
It won't bite you. It only bites me!

1046
01:41:44,933 --> 01:41:46,990
It has cancer, see?

1047
01:41:47,300 --> 01:41:48,526
It's cancer.

1048
01:41:48,933 --> 01:41:51,126
See, I have cancer. Stomach cancer.

1049
01:41:53,866 --> 01:41:55,491
It's cancer!

1050
01:42:06,367 --> 01:42:08,094
You know something?

1051
01:42:08,833 --> 01:42:12,424
Jesus Christ himself would
have died of stomach cancer...

1052
01:42:12,599 --> 01:42:15,861
if you people hadn't crucified him first!

1053
01:42:16,766 --> 01:42:18,823
That's right!

1054
01:43:06,066 --> 01:43:07,054
Bravo!

1055
01:44:53,499 --> 01:44:55,159
<i>Signor</i> Kracklite.

1056
01:45:13,833 --> 01:45:14,890
Name?

1057
01:45:16,733 --> 01:45:18,961
Kracklite, Stourley Kracklite.

1058
01:45:20,566 --> 01:45:22,759
- Nationality?
- American.

1059
01:45:25,766 --> 01:45:27,323
Place of birth?

1060
01:45:27,933 --> 01:45:29,626
Chicago, Illinois.

1061
01:45:31,267 --> 01:45:32,857
Present address?

1062
01:45:33,666 --> 01:45:34,757
Rome.

1063
01:45:36,833 --> 01:45:38,560
Age next birthday?

1064
01:45:39,233 --> 01:45:41,755
I'm not gonna have another birthday.

1065
01:45:41,833 --> 01:45:43,026
Pardon?

1066
01:45:44,599 --> 01:45:45,997
Fifty-five.

1067
01:45:47,733 --> 01:45:49,722
- Married?
- Yeah.

1068
01:45:50,866 --> 01:45:52,127
Children?

1069
01:45:55,133 --> 01:45:56,224
Yeah.

1070
01:45:57,933 --> 01:45:59,297
Occupation?

1071
01:46:00,599 --> 01:46:02,259
I'm an architect.

1072
01:46:04,499 --> 01:46:05,863
That's all.

1073
01:46:06,033 --> 01:46:08,555
Thank you. You may go.

1074
01:46:12,666 --> 01:46:14,825
You mean, that's really all?

1075
01:46:17,000 --> 01:46:18,989
What else could there be?

1076
01:47:29,233 --> 01:47:32,995
I'm sorry that we're late. It's my fault.
I don't feel very well.

1077
01:47:33,066 --> 01:47:36,191
We almost didn't make it.
Where's Kracklite?

1078
01:48:00,367 --> 01:48:01,992
I need to sit down.

1079
01:48:02,200 --> 01:48:06,427
Whatever else has happened,
this was always Kracklite's exhibition.

1080
01:48:06,933 --> 01:48:09,626
Louisa, can you find a way to help us...

1081
01:48:09,699 --> 01:48:12,188
and open up in his behalf?

1082
01:48:12,432 --> 01:48:14,864
Kracklite said a long time ago...

1083
01:48:14,933 --> 01:48:18,161
that you have often
officiated occasions like this:

1084
01:48:18,233 --> 01:48:20,755
Opening supermarkets, naval ships...

1085
01:48:21,499 --> 01:48:22,965
and cutting the tape.

1086
01:48:29,766 --> 01:48:31,755
I think Caspasian should do it.

1087
01:48:31,833 --> 01:48:34,197
Caspasian, this is not for you.

1088
01:48:34,799 --> 01:48:37,231
Be content with what you've got.

1089
01:48:43,499 --> 01:48:44,988
Here, take it.

1090
01:48:49,933 --> 01:48:51,126
Thanks.

1091
01:48:52,400 --> 01:48:53,388
Please.

1092
01:49:07,133 --> 01:49:10,587
We are delighted, <i>Signora</i> Kracklite,
that you have agreed to do this.

1093
01:49:10,666 --> 01:49:12,632
Louisa, please.

1094
01:49:13,100 --> 01:49:17,555
We can continue to benefit from the
prestige of an American celebrity.

1095
01:49:20,466 --> 01:49:22,489
Without the embarrassment...

1096
01:49:22,666 --> 01:49:24,326
of her clown of a husband.

1097
01:52:53,166 --> 01:52:56,495
And so, it is with great delight...

1098
01:52:56,633 --> 01:52:58,997
that on Boullée's birthday...

1099
01:52:59,333 --> 01:53:01,423
I ask <i>Signora</i> Kracklite...

1100
01:53:01,933 --> 01:53:05,421
to declare this magnificent
exhibition open.

1101
01:53:06,000 --> 01:53:09,117

